en\u00e9 Echevarria]]\n* Michael Thorn\n* [[Tony DiSanto]]\n* [[Liz Gateley]]\n* [[Russell Mulcahy]]\n* [[Joseph Genier|Joseph P. Genier]]\n* [[Tim Andrew]]\n* Karen Gorodetzky}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Eric Wallace\n* Blaine Williams\n* [[Tyler Posey]]\n* Ross Maxwell}}\n| composer                 = Dino Meneghin\n| cinematography           = Jonathan Hall<br />Rich Paisley<br />David Daniel\n| editor                   = Gabriel Flemming<br />Alyssa Clark<br />Gregory Cusumano<br />Edward R. Abroms<br />David Daniel<br />Kim Powell<br />[[Kevin Mock]]\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]]\n* [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]\n}}\n| runtime                  = 40-43 minutes (per episode)\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* Adelstein Productions\n* [[DiGa|DiGa Vision]]\n* First Cause, Inc.\n* Lost Marbles Television\n* [[MGM Television]]\n* MTV Production Development\n* Siesta Productions\n}}\n| distributor              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Viacom Media Networks]]\n* [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] (home video release)\n}}\n| network                  = [[MTV]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2011|6|5}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2017|9|24}}\n| related                  = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Teen Wolf]]''\n* ''[[Teen Wolf Too]]''\n* [[Teen Wolf (1986 TV series)|''Teen Wolf'' (1986 TV series)]]\n}}\n}}\n \n'''''Teen Wolf''''' i<!-- Do not change \"is\" to \"was\", it is still a series that exists even though it is no longer airing -->s an American [[supernatural fiction|supernatural]] [[teen drama]] television series developed by [[Jeff Davis (writer)|Jeff Davis]] for [[MTV]]. It i<!-- Do not change \"is\" to \"was\", it is still a series that exists even though it is no longer airing -->s loosely based on the [[Teen Wolf|1985 film of the same name]]. The series stars [[Tyler Posey]] as Scott McCall, a teenager who is bitten by a [[werewolf]], and [[Dylan O'Brien]] as \"Stiles\" Stilinski, Scott's best friend. The series received generally positive reviews from critics.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web |title=Teen Wolf: Season 1 |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/teen-wolf/season-1/critic-reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen-wolf/s01/ |title=Teen Wolf: Season 1 (2011-2011) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen-wolf/s02/ |title=Teen Wolf: Season 1 (2012) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen-wolf/s03/ |title=Teen Wolf: Season 3 (2013) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Teen Wolf'' premiered on June 5, 2011, following the [[2011 MTV Movie Awards]].<ref name=\"TeenWolfPremiere\" /> On July 21, 2016, the cast announced at [[San Diego Comic-Con|Comic Con]] that the sixth season would be the series' final.<ref>{{cite web |title='Teen Wolf' Ending After Season 6; MTV Unveils New Trailer at Comic-Con |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/teen-wolf-final-season-6-trailer-ending-1201819854/ |website=Variety |accessdate=July 22, 2016 |date=July 21, 2016 |first=Laura |last=Prudom}}</ref> The series finale aired on September 24, 2017.<ref name=\"sfinaledate\">{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2017/08/17/teen-wolf-series-finale-date-september-2017-airdate/ |title=''Teen Wolf'' Series Finale Date Set |last=Swift |first=Andy |date=August 17, 2017 |access-date=August 19, 2017 |website=TVLine}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe series revolves around [[Outcast (person)|social outcast]] Scott McCall, a high school student living in the town of Beacon Hills. Scott's life drastically changes when he is bitten by a werewolf the night before sophomore year, becoming one himself. He must henceforth learn to balance his problematic new identity with his day-to-day teenage life.\n\nIn season one, Scott and his human best friend \"Stiles\" Stilinski begin to encounter other characters with a connection to the supernatural goings-on in Beacon Hills. Scott's initial love interest is Allison Argent, a classmate of his who comes from a family of werewolf hunters. Her best friend is popular girl and genius Lydia Martin, who later discovers she is a [[banshee]]. Scott and Stiles routinely clash with Lydia's aggressive boyfriend, jock Jackson Whittemore, as well as Derek Hale, a mysterious werewolf with a dark past. As the show progresses, Scott is joined by new friends: Malia Tate, a werecoyote; Kira Yukimura, a [[kitsune]]; and Liam Dunbar, a young werewolf with anger issues.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{main|List of Teen Wolf characters}}\n<!-- NOTE; READ THIS NOTE: Per Wikipedia:WikiProject Television/Style guidelines#Cast information, \"The cast should be organized according to the series original broadcast credits, with new cast members being added to the end of the list. Please keep in mind that 'main' cast status is determined by the series producers, not by popularity or screen time. Furthermore, articles should reflect the entire history of a series, and as such actors remain on the list even after their departure from the series.\" NOTE; READ THE ABOVE NOTE. -->\n<!--DO NOT ADD SEASON 6 WITHOUT SOURCES-->\n* [[Tyler Posey]] as Scott McCall: Scott is turned into a werewolf in the series premiere and, alongside his friend Stiles, begins to uncover the complicated supernatural world of Beacon Hills, California.\n* [[Crystal Reed]] as Allison Argent (seasons 1\u20133, guest season 5): Scott's love interest, Allison, descends from a long line of werewolf hunters. Her formidable prowess with a bow and arrow is an asset to the team in encounters with the shapeshifters and monsters that roam Beacon Hills.\n* [[Dylan O'Brien]] as Stiles<!-- please do not add \"Mieczyslaw\" as that is not his common name and not how he is referred to throughtout the series --> Stilinski: Stiles is Scott's childhood best friend, with a talent for solving mysteries and a fierce loyalty to those closest to him.\n* [[Tyler Hoechlin]] as Derek Hale (seasons 1\u20134, guest season 6): An older werewolf from a prominent werewolf family in Beacon Hills, Derek starts off with a hostile relationship towards Scott and his \"pack\" of friends, but comes to be a valuable ally.\n* [[Holland Roden]] as Lydia Martin: A popular girl at Beacon Hills High and a close friend of Allison's, Lydia initially tries to play down her formidable intelligence; she is a genius. After an encounter with Derek's villainous uncle Peter Hale in season one, her own supernatural abilities&mdash;those of a [[banshee]]&mdash;begin to manifest.\n* [[Colton Haynes]] as Jackson Whittemore (seasons 1\u20132, guest season 6): Lydia's shallow boyfriend. Jackson antagonises Scott and Stiles relentlessly but suffers from inner self-hatred. This causes his encounter with a werewolf's claws to turn him into another sort of creature: the deadly reptilian kanima. Jackson abruptly leaves Beacon Hills in the gap between seasons two and three, but returns for a guest stint at the end of season six, having [[coming out|come out]] and entered a relationship with another werewolf, Ethan.\n* [[Shelley Hennig]] as Malia Tate (recurring season 3; main seasons 4\u20136): The daughter of Peter Hale and a werecoyote assassin, Malia was adopted into a local Beacon Hills family for her own safety. After her new family is killed, she spends her formative years as a fully transformed feral coyote. After rejoining the human social world, she develops a blunt, no-nonsense personality, while adjusting to teenage life as a [[Wikt:fish out of water|fish out of water]].\n* [[Arden Cho]] as Kira Yukimura (recurring season 3; main seasons 4\u20135):<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/755902/teen-wolf-shocker-arden-cho-is-leaving-the-show-ahead-of-season-6 |title=Teen Wolf Shocker: Arden Cho Is Leaving the Show |date=April 11, 2016 |accessdate=April 12, 2016 |work=E! Online}}</ref> Kira moves to Beacon Hills as monsters from Japanese mythology are beginning to plague the lives of her new classmates; she herself discovers that she is a thunder [[kitsune]] with profound swordsmanship skills and electrical powers.\n* [[Dylan Sprayberry]] as Liam Dunbar (recurring season 4; main seasons 5\u20136): Liam is a younger rival of Scott's with anger issues who Scott is forced to transform into a werewolf in order to save his life. Liam's anger gives him an uncommon degree of strength for a young werewolf, and he comes to develop a real respect for his mentor, Scott.\n* [[Linden Ashby]] as Sheriff Stilinski (recurring seasons 1\u20135; main season 6):<ref name=\"6titles\">{{cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/202584_watch_new_teen_wolf_opening_titles_for_final_season/ |title='Teen Wolf' Season 6 opening tiles features some familiar faces |date=November 14, 2016 |website=Entertainment Tonight}}</ref> Stiles' father is initially reluctant to help his son and Scott with their escapades but is later brought into their supernatural secret. From then on, he assists his son by deploying the resources of the police department to help when he can.\n* [[Melissa Ponzio]] as Melissa McCall (recurring seasons 1\u20135; main season 6):<ref name=\"6titles\" /> Scott's mother, a local nurse, becomes an invaluable ally of the gang once brought in on their secret, concealing unexplained supernatural occurrences and saving the lives of Scott and his pack members many times over.\n* [[JR Bourne]] as Chris Argent (recurring seasons 1\u20135; main season 6):<ref name=\"6titles\" /> Allison's father is a born and raised werewolf hunter who is highly effective at what he does. He later comes around to see Scott as a vital protector of Beacon Hills and dedicates himself to supporting his cause.\n*[[Daniella Rahme]] as Nicole Haddad (recurring Season 4-6): A mysterious woman who assisted Scott on how to become an Alpha.\nShe was once part of Deucalion's pack. Her status as an Alpha makes her a dangerous adversary.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Teen Wolf episodes}}\n''Teen Wolf'' premiered on June 5, 2011, following the [[2011 MTV Movie Awards]].<ref name=\"TeenWolfPremiere\">{{cite web |last=Bricker |first=Tierney |date=February 2, 2011 |title='Teen Wolf': MTV announces premiere date |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/teen-wolf-mtv-sets-premiere-date.html |work=[[Zap2it]] |accessdate=June 8, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612101402/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/teen-wolf-mtv-sets-premiere-date.html |archivedate=June 12, 2011 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The second season premiered on June 3, 2012, after the [[2012 MTV Movie Awards]]. On July 12, 2012, ''Teen Wolf'' was renewed for a third season, which includes 24 episodes and the production location was moved to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite news |title='Teen Wolf' Renewed |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/12/teen-wolf-renewed-season-3_n_1669776.html |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |accessdate=July 25, 2012 |first=Maggie |last=Furlong |date=July 12, 2012}}</ref> \n\nThe third season premiered on June 3, 2013, at 10 pm,<ref>{{cite web |last=Swift |first=Andy |title='Teen Wolf' Season 3 Premiere Date Revealed |url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2013/02/19/teen-wolf-season-3-premiere-date-june-3-2013/ |work=Hollywood Life |publisher=PMC |accessdate=March 25, 2013|date=February 19, 2013 }}</ref> giving the series a new high on ratings.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tv-ratings-mtvs-teen-wolf-562702 |title=TV Ratings: MTV's 'Teen Wolf' Hits Highs With Season 3 Premiere |work=The Hollywood Reporter |last=O'Connell |first=Michael |date=April 6, 2011 |accessdate=June 26, 2013}}</ref> A fourth season premiered on June 23, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shaefer |first=Megan |title='Teen Wolf' Season 4 Spoilers |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/teen-wolf-season-4-spoilers-premiere-date-revealed-what-character-wont-be-returning-june-23-1563647 |date=March 26, 2014 |accessdate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> On July 24, 2014, MTV renewed ''Teen Wolf'' for a fifth season of 20 episodes, which was split into two parts, and premiered June 29, 2015.<ref name=\"releasedate\">{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/MTVteenwolf/status/576186026638462976 |title=TEEN WOLF on Twitter |work=Twitter |date=March 12, 2015 |accessdate=March 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Season5Renewed\">{{cite web |last=Slezak |first=Michael |title=MTV Renews Teen Wolf for Season 5 |url=http://tvline.com/2014/07/24/teen-wolf-renewed-season-5-mtv-20-episodes/ |work=TVLine |date=July 24, 2014 |accessdate=July 24, 2014}}</ref> \n\nOn July 9, 2015, ''Teen Wolf'' was renewed for a sixth season of 20 episodes. Showrunner [[Jeff Davis (writer)|Jeff Davis]] confirmed that [[Tyler Posey]], [[Dylan O'Brien]], [[Holland Roden]], [[Shelley Hennig]] and [[Dylan Sprayberry]] would be reprising their roles as Scott McCall, \"Stiles\" Stilinski, Lydia Martin, Malia Tate and Liam Dunbar respectively.<ref name=\"Season6\">{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Kaitlin |title=MTV Renews Teen Wolf for Season 6! Plus: Watch the INTENSE Trailer for the Rest of Season 5 (VIDEO) |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/teen-wolf-2011/community/post/teen-wolf-renewed-season-6-mtv-143646365515/ |website=TV.com |date=July 10, 2015 |accessdate=May 28, 2016}}</ref>\n{{:List of Teen Wolf episodes}}\n\n==Development and production==\n{{main|Mythology of Teen Wolf}}\nIn June 2009, MTV announced that they would be adapting the 1985 film ''[[Teen Wolf]]'' into a new television series \"with a greater emphasis on romance, horror and werewolf mythology\".<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite news |date=June 23, 2009 |author=Jon Weisman |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118005302.html |title=MTV greenlights eight projects |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=October 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMTV's ''Teen Wolf'' series was a re-imagining of the earlier [[Michael J. Fox]] comedy film, which was itself a reimagining of the classic 1957 [[American International Pictures|AIP]] film, ''[[I Was a Teenage Werewolf]]''. The film had been previously adapted for television, as an [[Teen Wolf (1986 TV series)|animated series]] aired on [[CBS]] in 1986\u201387.\n\nFor the MTV series, creator and executive producer, [[Jeff Davis (writer)|Jeff Davis]], aimed to develop a darker, sexier and edgier version than the 1985 film. Davis' desire was to make a [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]] with comedic overtones but in a tone more similar to that of the 1987 vampire film ''[[The Lost Boys]]''. According to Davis, it all started with an idea to do a homage to ''[[Stand by Me (film)|Stand by Me]]'', where in the beginning, the kids go out and search for a body in the woods and it's not quite what they expect.<ref name=\"collider\" /> The look of the show was inspired in part by [[Guillermo del Toro]]'s creatures in ''[[Pan's Labyrinth]]''; the producers described the werewolves as beautiful, elegant and scary, at the same time.<ref name=\"collider\" />\n\nOnce the show was a go, Davis lined up Australian director [[Russell Mulcahy]], who added the horror to the project.<ref name=\"collider\">{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/jeff-davis-russell-mulcahy-interview-teen-wolf/94736/ |title=Exclusive: Producer Jeff Davis and Director Russell Mulcahy Talk TEEN WOLF |last=Radish |first=Christina |date=June 10, 2011 |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=June 14, 2011}}</ref> Mulcahy directed the [[television pilot|pilot]] presentation and serves as executive producer and in-house director.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35640/russell-mulcahy-piloting-mtvs-teen-wolf-twilight-glory |date=July 20, 2012 |title=Russell Mulcahy Piloting MTV's Teen Wolf to Twilight Glory |website=Dreadcentral.com |accessdate=October 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Teen Wolf 2011 Title card.jpg|thumb|left|The title card from season one.]]\nCasting announcements were all announced in December 2010, with the main cast being, [[Tyler Posey]], [[Crystal Reed]], [[Tyler Hoechlin]], [[Dylan O'Brien]], [[Holland Roden]], and [[Colton Haynes]]. Posey was cast as the lead Scott McCall, a dorky high-school student who after being bitten by a werewolf, starts to notice changes in himself, Reed playing Allison Argent, a sweet new girl at school who is immediately attracted to Scott, Hoechlin playing Derek Hale, a handsome local boy who in fact is a vicious and predatory werewolf, and O'Brien playing Stiles, Scott's best friend. Roden playing Lydia Martin, Jackson Whittemore's popular and controlling girlfriend, and Haynes playing Jackson Whittemore, Scott's lacrosse teammate and rival.<ref>{{cite web |title=Breaking News -Development Update: Monday, December 14 |url=http://thefutoncritic.com/news/2009/12/14/development-update-monday-december-14-33839/8425/ |work=The Futon Critic |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nProduction on twelve episodes began in October 2010 in Atlanta, Georgia.<ref name=\"MTVpress\">{{cite web |url=http://thefutoncritic.com/news/2010/08/06/mtv-builds-slate-of-scripted-programming-with-2011-premieres-of-original-series-teen-wolf-and-skins-36898/20100806mtv01/ |title=MTV Builds Slate of Scripted Programming with 2011 Premieres of Original Series \"Teen Wolf\" and \"Skins\" |work=The Futon Critic |accessdate=November 25, 2010}}</ref> MTV released a sneak peek of the first eight minutes of the pilot on their website, on May 31, 2011. ''Teen Wolf'' episodes are composed by music composer Dino Meneghin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1567432/fullcredits|title=Teen Wolf (TV Series 2011\u20132017)|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> As of Season 2, the opening credits of the show changed dramatically to a longer format featuring the main characters appearing whilst performing an action (such as Colton Haynes performing a lacrosse throw), along with the respective names of the actors.\n\nThe new opening credits also feature the show's new theme song.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/06/01/teen-wolf-opening-credits-exclusive-video/ |title='Teen Wolf': Watch the very sexy (and very wet) new opening credits -- EXCLUSIVE VIDEO |work=Entertainment Weekly |author=Tim Stack |accessdate=June 9, 2012}}</ref> In June 2012, the series received conditional approval for a California film and TV tax credit.<ref name=\"lat120604\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-state-film-tax-credit-20120604,0,5618579.story |title=MTV show 'Teen Wolf' takes a bite out of state film tax credits |first=Richard |last=Verrier |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 4, 2012 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> At [[San Diego Comic-Con|Comic-Con 2012]], the cast confirmed that the show had been renewed for a longer third season, comprising twenty-four episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ux5Z4Bb9a-U |title=SDCC 2012: Official Teen Wolf Panel Video (Part 1) |author=sausage2}}</ref> In June 2013, the series was selected again for a California tax credit.<ref name=\"DL130604\">{{cite news |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/06/california-production-tax-lottery-winners-2013-full-list/ |title='Entourage' Movie, 'Justified', 'Teen Wolf' & 'King And Maxwell' Among Winners Of California Tax Credit Production Lottery |first=Dominic |last=Patten |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=June 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Differences and similarities from films==\n''Teen Wolf'' shares no continuity with the 1985 film ''[[Teen Wolf]]'' or its sequel, ''[[Teen Wolf Too]]'',<ref>{{cite news |author=MICHAEL WILMINGTON |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-11-20/entertainment/ca-15033_1_lycanthropy |title=MOVIE REVIEWS : 'Teen Wolf Too' Deserves a Silver Bullet - Los Angeles Times |website=LA Times |date=November 20, 1987 |accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0DE4D61639F933A15752C1A961948260 |title=Teen Wolf Too (1987), Family Curse |website=New York Times |accessdate=August 23, 2012 |first=Caryn |last=James |date=November 20, 1987}}</ref> but does contain allusions to the film which inspired its premise. The original film is about a typical awkward basketball-playing teenager named Scott dealing with high school and life as a [[werewolf]].<ref name=\"cnn\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/features/channel-guide-teen-wolf-barks-but-doesnt-bite-yet.php |title=Channel Guide: 'Teen Wolf' Barks, But Doesn't Bite Yet |last=Barr |first=Merrill |date=June 11, 2011 |website=Film School Rejects |accessdate=June 11, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69BwxjzmM?url=http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/features/channel-guide-teen-wolf-barks-but-doesnt-bite-yet.php |archivedate=July 16, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In both the film and show, Scott reaps the benefits of werewolf stardom, achieving confidence and acceptance from his peers with his newly-discovered powers, and has a close friend named Stiles. In the 1985 movie, Scott played basketball, whereas in the series, he plays [[lacrosse]]; Stiles wears retro British T-shirts in the TV series rather than the offensive T-shirts of the film; and Scott is transformed into a werewolf by bite in the series, whereas in the film he inherits the trait from his father.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news |url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2011/06/09/the-throwback-did-teen-wolf-need-a-reboot/ |title=The Throwback: Did 'Teen Wolf' need a reboot? |last=McLaughlin |first=Katie |date=June 9, 2011 |website=CNN |accessdate=June 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhile the ''Teen Wolf'' film is a comedy, the MTV series is a drama which includes dark themes, violence, and gore, as well as comedic elements; series developer [[Jeff Davis (writer)|Jeff Davis]] and other producers have referred to their indebtedness to [[Joss Whedon]]'s supernatural drama ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''. Davis comments that ''Buffy''{{'}}s central metaphor was \"[h]igh school as a horror movie. And so the metaphor became the central concept behind ''Buffy'', and that's how I sold [''Teen Wolf''].\"{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} The writers decided early on to exclude vampires from their in-show mythology.<ref name=\"novamps\">{{cite news |url=http://eonline.com/uberblog/the_awful_truth/b254377_will_teen_wolf_be_venturing_into.html |title=Will Teen Wolf Be Venturing Into Vampire Territory? |last=Casablanca |first=Ted |last2=Boone |first2=John |date=July 26, 2011 |website=[[E!]] |accessdate=July 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809161012/http://www.eonline.com/news/the_awful_truth/will_teen_wolf_be_venturing_into/254377 |archive-date=August 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#DF7A59;\"|\n| [[Teen Wolf (season 1)#Reception|1]]\n| 68% (25 reviews)<ref name=\"TeenWolfS1RT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen_wolf/s01|title=Teen Wolf: Season 1 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n| 61 (14 reviews)<ref name=MetacriticS1>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/teen-wolf/season-1|title=Teen Wolf: Season 1 |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#251A14;\"|\n| [[Teen Wolf (season 2)#Reception|2]]\n| 90% (10 reviews)<ref name=\"TeenWolfS2RT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen_wolf/s02|title=Teen Wolf: Season 2 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#090C15;\"|\n| [[Teen Wolf (season 3)#Reception|3]]\n| 88% (17 reviews)<ref name=\"TeenWolfS3RT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen_wolf/s03|title=Teen Wolf: Season 3 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#B1ACA8;\"|\n| [[Teen Wolf (season 4)#Reception|4]]\n| 67% (12 reviews)<ref name=\"TeenWolfS4RT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen_wolf/s04|title=Teen Wolf: Season 4 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#141414;\"|\n| [[Teen Wolf (season 5)#Reception|5]]\n| 92% (12 reviews)<ref name=\"TeenWolfS5RT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen_wolf/s05|title=Teen Wolf: Season 5 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#2A4948;\"|\n| [[Teen Wolf (season 6)#Reception|6]]\n| 83% (12 reviews)<ref name=\"TeenWolfS6RT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/teen_wolf/s06|title=Teen Wolf: Season 6 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n|}\n\nThe first season of the series generated a generally positive response from professional critics, with some praising it as better quality when compared to other shows by [[MTV]]. According to [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the show holds an average score of 61 out of 100, which indicates \"Generally favorable reviews\", based on fourteen reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> Metacritic also lists the show as the second-highest rated [[MTV]] series by professional critics behind ''[[Awkward (TV series)|Awkward]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=MTV: MTV's Scores |url=http://www.metacritic.com/company/mtv?page=4 |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=June 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nReview aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 68% of 25 critics have given the first season a positive review. The site's consensus is: \"Thanks to a charismatic lead in Tyler Posey and some dark, biting humor, Teen Wolf is a pleasant summer surprise, even if it does tread familiar ground.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\"/> Linda Stasi, a writer from the ''[[New York Post]]'', awarded the series' premiere a perfect score, stating, \"Not only is it really well thought out, but the good-looking kids in the show can actually act.\"<ref name=\"NYP\">{{cite news |last=Stasi |first=Linda |date=May 23, 2011 |title=Fangs-giving Day: 'Teen Wolf' lives up to the expectations |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/tv/fangs_giving_day_sink_in_your_fangs_2tLWTopp0rrxDU0qIRgdcI |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref> Verne Gay from ''[[Newsday]]'' also reserved high praise for the show, calling it a \"winner and best of all, fun\".<ref name=\"ND\">{{cite web |last=Gay |first=Verne |date=June 1, 2011 |title='Teen Wolf': Boys will be werewolves |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/teen-wolf-boys-will-be-werewolves-1.2920568 |work=[[Newsday]] |accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref> David Hinckley of [[New York Daily News|New York ''Daily News'']] commented favorably on the series, ending his review with \"Werewolves, pretty girls, dumb bullies and lacrosse. What more, really, could you ask of high school?\"<ref name=\"NYDN\">{{cite news |last=Hinckley |first=David |date=June 3, 2011 |title=Room for one more: 'Teen Wolf' will have 'em howling for another wistfully romantic fantasy |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2011/06/03/2011-06-03_teen_wolf_will_have_em_howling_for_more.html |work=[[New York Daily News]] |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> Film critic [[Rex Reed]] is a fan of the series, calling it \"the sexiest show on television today.\"\n\nSome critics had a less positive reaction toward the first episode. Troy Patterson from ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' gave it a mixed review, referring to it as \"light and passably witty supernatural drama\".<ref name=\"Slate\">{{cite web |last=Patterson |first=Troy |date=June 3, 2011 |title=Teen Wolf: MTV updates the classic teen movie with more scares, more sex, and lacrosse. |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2296052/ |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref> James Poniewozik from ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine also had mixed feelings towards the show, saying, \"The pilot isn't bad, exactly\u2014it's well-paced if a little dour in spots and there's some decent CW-esque banter\u2014but it's pretty much entirely what I would have expected from any supernatural teen drama\".<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news |last=Poniewozik |first=James |date=June 3, 2011 |title=TV Weekend: Teen Wolf |url=http://tunedin.blogs.time.com/2011/06/03/tv-weekend-teen-wolf/ |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> Following the first-season finale in August 2011, Ian Grey of [[indieWire]] gave the series a positive review<ref name=\"indieWire\">{{cite web |last=Grey |first=Ian |date=August 21, 2011 |title=GREY MATTERS: With ALPHAS, TEEN WOLF and FALLING SKIES, genre TV mourns the loss of family |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/pressplay/archives/2011/08/21/GREY_MATTERS_With_Alphas_Teen_Wolf_Falling_Skies_TV_mourns_the_loss_of/ |work=[[indieWire]] |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and Angel Cohn of [[Television Without Pity]] named it the third best new show of the summer.<ref name=\"twop\">{{cite web |last=Cohn |first=Angel |date=August 26, 2011 |title=TWoP 10: Best New Scripted Shows of This Summer |url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/telefile/2011/08/twop-10-best-new-scripted-summ.php |work=[[Television Without Pity]] |accessdate=August 27, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69Bx7gFs8?url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/telefile/2011/08/twop-10-best-new-scripted-summ.php |archivedate=July 16, 2012 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[BuddyTV]] ranked ''Teen Wolf'' #4 on its list of 2011's best new TV shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buddytv.com/slideshows/game-of-thrones/the-11-best-new-tv-shows-of-2011-84679.aspx |title=The 11 Best New TV Shows of 2011 |website=[[BuddyTV]] |accessdate=January 13, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107225959/http://www.buddytv.com/slideshows/game-of-thrones/the-11-best-new-tv-shows-of-2011-84679.aspx# |archive-date=January 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe second season of the show received even more positive reviews than the first, with Rotten Tomatoes reporting a 90% approval rating based on 10 critical reviews.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com2\"/> The third season also received positive reviews, earning an approval rating of 88% based on 17 reviews.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com3\"/>\n\nDespite its generally positive reception, the show has struggled with representation of [[LGBTQ]] characters and issues, and been critiqued for [[queerbaiting]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/teen-wolf-bisexuality-representation-jackson |title=How Teen Wolf Missed The Mark for Bisexuality Representation |work=[[Teen Vogue]] |accessdate=June 17, 2018 |date=September 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.advocate.com/commentary/2014/09/17/op-ed-trouble-teen-wolf |title=Op-ed: The Trouble With ''Teen Wolf'' |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |accessdate=June 17, 2018 |date=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{{see also|List of Teen Wolf episodes#Ratings}}\nThe series premiere attracted a total of 2.17 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/06/07/sunday-cable-ratings-mtv-movie-awards-leads-night-game-of-thrones-series-high-real-housewives-abdc-lots-more/94914/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'MTV Movie Awards' Leads Night, 'Game of Thrones' Series High, 'Real Housewives,' 'ABDC' & Lots More |work=TV by the Numbers |last=Gorman |first=Bill |date=June 7, 2011 |accessdate=June 22, 2011}}</ref> After airing its third episode, ''Teen Wolf'' was reported to be heading into its fourth week with tremendous momentum following a 23 percent increase among persons 12\u201334, with a 1.6 in the demo. With double digit percentage gains among total viewers and key demos, ''Teen Wolf'' was the #1 show in its timeslot with women 12\u201334.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/06/14/teen-wolf-roars-in-its-third-outing-with-double-digit-gains-among-total-viewers-and-key-demos/95649/ |title='Teen Wolf' Roars In Its Third Outing, With Double Digit Gains Among Total Viewers And Key Demos |last=Gorman |first=Bill |date=June 14, 2011 |website=tv by numbers |accessdate=June 14, 2011}}</ref> The first-season finale attained a series high in persons 12\u201334 (1.9) and 2.1 million viewers overall, as well as being first in its timeslot among teens and females 12\u201334.<ref name=\"s1finale\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/teen-wolf-closes-season-high-223728 |title='Teen Wolf' Closes Out Season on High Ratings Note |last=Ng |first=Philiana |date=August 16, 2011 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe show's creator, [[Jeff Davis (writer)|Jeff Davis]] confirmed that the show benefits from a very significant online viewership, with up to eight million streams per episode on MTV's online platforms alone. Davis cited this as a significant contributing factor to MTV renewing the show for a sixth season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/teen-wolf-renewed-for-season-6-1201473159/ |title='MTV's 'Teen Wolf' Renewed For Season 6 \u2013 Comic Con' |accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Television season ratings\n| hide_18_49_rating = y\n| hide_rank = y\n\n| link1     = Teen Wolf (season 1)\